[5] Argentina
Date: Tue 31 Mar 2020
Source: ProMED ESP Vol 10, Issue 80 [edited]
https://www.infobae.com/salud/2020/03/28/ya-son-2942-los-casos-de-dengue-y-158-los-de-sarampion-en-la-argentina/ and
https://www.newsmaker.news/a/2020/03/there-are-already-2942-dengue-cases-and-158-measles-cases-in-argentina.html


There are already 2942 dengue cases and 158 measles cases in Argentina.

...Since the beginning of 2019, there were 158 cases of measles confirmed in Argentina and one death: 109 cases in the past year (7 imported or related to import, 2 cases detected in Spain, and 100 of unknown origin) and 49 in 2020 (9 imported and 40 of unknown origin).

Of the total, one case was in the province of Cordoba that had a history of travel to Florianopolis, Brazil; 28 cases in the city of Buenos Aires and 120 in the province of Buenos Aires, in 19 games: Tres de Febrero, Almirante Brown, Avellaneda, Berazategui, General San Martin, Hurlingham, Ituzaingo, La Matanza, Lanus, Lomas de Zamora, Malvinas Argentinas, Marcos Paz, Merlo, Moreno, Moron, Pilar, Quilmes, Tigre and Vicente Lopez.

The greatest number of confirmed measles cases are in children under one year of age, where the highest incidence rate is also observed, followed by groups from 1-4 years. However, the number of cases in adults older than 20 years is significant.

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), between 30 and 40 million people contracted measles in 2000, and there were 777 000 deaths. Additionally, between 2000 and 2017, measles vaccination decreased the death toll by 80% worldwide.

